Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code for your `BackgroundProcessor`.

## Pattern Classification

| Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` + `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `GetNextItem()` (may block) | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to unblock |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic as the old
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we just continue to the
                // loop condition, which will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — replaces Thread.Abort

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — cooperative, not preemptive.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when` guard prevents catching unrelated OCEs.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — the loop condition (`!token.IsCancellationRequested`) handles continuation naturally.
4. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Thread.Join(2s)`** — actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping and hoping.
5. **`IDisposable` added** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed.

## Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Accept the Token

The old code relied on `Thread.Abort` to forcibly interrupt a blocking `GetNextItem()`. **Cooperative cancellation won't interrupt it unless the method checks the token.** You must update it:

```csharp
// If backed by a BlockingCollection<T>:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OCE when cancelled
}

// If backed by a manual wait:
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!_dataReady.WaitOne(500))
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls synchronous I/O you don't control (e.g., `socket.Receive`), replace it with an async overload (`await ReceiveAsync(token)`) or use a polling loop with short timeouts that checks the token between attempts.

**If you skip this step, `Stop()` will hang** — the thread will block inside `GetNextItem` forever because nothing forcibly interrupts it anymore. This is the #1 migration failure mode.
